In a single research project, data collection usually takes place in multiple locations and at several time points. At each site location multiple samples are usually taken, which are used to capture variation in a study area or time-period. In Darwin Core, each of these samples and site locations in Darwin Core are known as Events.

Events refer to any action that “occurs at some location during some time.” (from TDWG). Each sample, for example, is a unique event, with its own environmental attributes (like topography, tree cover, precipitation and soil composition) that affect what organisms occur there and how likely they are to occur. Observations of organisms take place within each Event. As such, Events add hierarchy to a dataset (as opposed to occurrences-only data which is processed as if all occurrences take place in a single “Event”), which adds richness to ecological data that can be useful for more advanced modelling techniques.

Here we will demonstrate an example of converting data with Events and Occurrences to Darwin Core standard. These data will be saved as two csv files, events.csv and occurrences.csv, and used to build a Darwin Core Archive.
